</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,1857,2027]" lastBlockId="35.[189,1398,267,410]" lastPageId="35" lastPageNumber="36" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Among the original material of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" authorityYear="1842" box="[563,716,1857,1883]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[563,716,1857,1883]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Ophiacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
? 
<taxonomicName authority="Hess" authorityName="Hess" authorityYear="1962" box="[736,994,1857,1884]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Dermocoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="toarcensis">
<taxonomicName box="[736,856,1858,1883]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="species" species="toarcensis">
<emphasis box="[736,856,1858,1883]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">toarcensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Hess H." box="[863,994,1857,1884]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="609 - 656" refId="ref122260" refString="Hess H. 1962. Mikropalaontologische Untersuchungen an Ophiuren II: Die Ophiuren aus dem Lias (Pliensbachien-Toarcien) von Seewen (Kt. Solothurn). Eclogae geologicae Helvetiae 55: 609 - 656." type="journal article" year="1962">Hess, 1962</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the Toarcian of 
<collectingCountry box="[1251,1394,1857,1883]" name="Switzerland" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
, here reassigned to 
<taxonomicName authority="Hess" authorityName="Hess" authorityYear="1964" box="[403,683,1893,1920]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Dermocoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<taxonomicName box="[403,548,1894,1919]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Dermocoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[403,548,1894,1919]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Dermocoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation author="Hess H." box="[554,683,1893,1920]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="756 - 801" refId="ref122328" refString="Hess H. 1964. Die Ophiuren des englischen Jura. Eclogae geologicae Helvetiae 57: 756 - 801." type="journal article" year="1964">Hess, 1964</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(see below), is a single 
<potCollectionCode box="[957,1011,1893,1919]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">LAP</potCollectionCode>
which obviously does not belong to that species. 
<collectionCode box="[366,386,1929,1955]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15406" name="Harvard University - Arnold Arboretum" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="Herbarium">A</collectionCode>
detailed re-examination of that plate has revealed that it is a species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Thuy, 2013" authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[1215,1342,1929,1955]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Lapidaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1215,1342,1929,1955]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Lapidaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, on account of its 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. L. Clark" authorityYear="1911" box="[458,624,1965,1991]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiomyxidae" genus="Ophiologimus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[458,624,1965,1991]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Ophiologimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like morphology and the presence of spurs on the outer proximal and inner distal edges. The unusually small spine articulations composed of separated dorsal and ventral lobes, as well as the presence of a second, strongly developed spur in the centre of the outer proximal and inner distal edges sets the 
<potCollectionCode box="[544,598,306,332]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">LAP</potCollectionCode>
in question quite apart from other 
<potCollectionCode box="[1003,1057,306,332]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">LAP</potCollectionCode>
<typeStatus box="[1065,1127,306,332]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">types</typeStatus>
assigned to 
<taxonomicName authority="Thuy, 2013" authorityName="Thuy" authorityYear="2013" box="[1271,1398,306,332]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Lapidaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiurida" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1271,1398,306,332]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Lapidaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[189,296,345,371]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
It unquestionably represents a distinct, undescribed species. Unfortunately, only a single 
<potCollectionCode box="[1344,1398,345,371]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">LAP</potCollectionCode>
is currently known, which precludes the formal description of a new species.
</paragraph>
